04315nam a22006615i 9780226285009DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t20082006ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802262850097 a10.7208/97802262850092doi  a(DE-B1597)524330  a(OCoLC)1135592759  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aJK2281 7aPOL0000002bisacsh0481pa324.730973222/oclc1 aGeer, John G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Defense of Negativity :bAttack Ads in Presidential Campaigns /cJohn G. Geer. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (218 p.) :b32 line drawings, 12 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Communication, Media, and Public Opinion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Need for Negativity: An Introduction -- t2. Assessing Negativity -- t3. The Information Environment and Negativity -- t4. Evaluating Character A -- t5. Evaluating the Content of Negative and Positive Issue Appeals -- t6. Dragging the Truth into the Gutter? The News Media, Negativity and the 1988 Campaign -- t7. Negativity, Democracy, and the Political System -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmericans tend to see negative campaign ads as just that: negative. Pundits, journalists, voters, and scholars frequently complain that such ads undermine elections and even democratic government itself. But John G. Geer here takes the opposite stance, arguing that when political candidates attack each other, raising doubts about each other’s views and qualifications, voters—and the democratic process—benefit. In Defense of Negativity, Geer’s study of negative advertising in presidential campaigns from 1960 to 2004, asserts that the proliferating attack ads are far more likely than positive ads to focus on salient political issues, rather than politicians’ personal characteristics. Accordingly, the ads enrich the democratic process, providing voters with relevant and substantial information before they head to the polls. An important and timely contribution to American political discourse, In Defense of Negativity concludes that if we want campaigns to grapple with relevant issues and address real problems, negative ads just might be the solution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aAdvertising, PoliticalxUnited States. 0aAdvertising, PoliticalzUnited States. 0aCampagnes électoralesxGestionxÉtats-Unis. 0aCampagnes électoralesxÉtats-Unis. 0aCampaign managementxUnited States. 0aCampaign managementzUnited States. 0aNegativism. 0aNégativismexVerenigde StatenxUnited States. 0aPolitical campaignsxUnited States. 0aPolitical campaignszUnited States. 0aPresidentsxElectionxHistoryxUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectionxHistory. 0aPrésidentsxÉlectionxHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 0aPublicité politiquexÉtats-Unis. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226285009423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226285009.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles